\begin_layout Part Introduction (ClassicThesis)
This chapter presents a complete theory of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{\mathrm{exc}}$
\end_inset

 evaluation under HRF approximation.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

As presented in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chpt:mdft"

\end_inset

, to complete the minimization process of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
acs{MDFT}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we need to evaluate the excess functional
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{F}_{\mathrm{exc}}=-\frac{k_{\mathrm{B}}T}{2}\int\mathrm{d}\mathbf{r}_{1}\mathrm{d}\mathbf{r}_{2}\mathrm{d}\mathbf{\Omega}_{1}\mathrm{d}\mathbf{\Omega}_{2}\Delta\rho(\mathbf{r}_{1},\mathbf{\Omega}_{1})\Delta\rho(\mathbf{r}_{2},\mathbf{\Omega}_{2})c(\mathbf{r}_{12},\mathbf{\Omega}_{1},\mathbf{\Omega}_{2})\tag{II.1}\label{eq:fexc-II}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

as well as its gradient (normalized as dimensionless)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\gamma(\mathbf{r}_{1},\mathbf{\Omega}_{1})=\int\mathrm{d}\mathbf{r}_{2}\mathrm{d}\mathbf{\Omega}_{2}\Delta\rho(\mathbf{r}_{2},\mathbf{\Omega}_{2})c(\mathbf{r}_{12},\mathbf{\Omega}_{1},\mathbf{\Omega}_{2})\tag{II.2}\label{eq:gamma-II}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

As discussed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathsection$
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:The-excess-term"

\end_inset

, eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:gamma-II"

\end_inset

) is a 3D convolution, which leads to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\gamma}(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{\Omega}_{1})=\int\mathrm{d}\mathbf{\Omega}_{2}\Delta\hat{\rho}(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{\Omega}_{2})\hat{c}(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{\Omega}_{1},\mathbf{\Omega}_{2})\tag{II.3}\label{eq:gamma-k-II}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

such that the integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\int\mathrm{d}\mathbf{r}_{2}$
\end_inset

 in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:gamma-II"

\end_inset

) is transformed into a simple product in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:gamma-k-II"

\end_inset

), giving a great advantage in terms of computational efficiency for huge
 spatial grid.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

In the previous work 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Zhao_2011"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{c}(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{\Omega}_{1},\mathbf{\Omega}_{2})$
\end_inset

 in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:gamma-k-II"

\end_inset

) is evaluated with a pre- tabulated intermolecular 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
acs{DCF}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{c}(k,\cos\theta_{1},\cos\theta_{2},\phi_{12})$
\end_inset

, which is appropriate for linear molecules.
 Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chpt:fft-spatial"

\end_inset

 gives a complete evaluation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{c}(\mathbf{k},\mathbf{\Omega}_{1},\mathbf{\Omega}_{2})$
\end_inset

 using either a full intermolecular 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
acs{DCF}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{c}(k,\cos\theta_{1},\cos\theta_{2},\phi_{12},\psi_{1},\psi_{2})$
\end_inset

 or rotational invariant projections.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

On the other hand, the increased precision of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
acs{DCF}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 evaluation makes the computing cost of the original algorithm no longer
 reasonable.
 Further approximation should be therefore made.
 Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chpt:angular-convolution"

\end_inset

 presents a new algorithm to treat the angular convolution in eq.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:gamma-k-II"

\end_inset

), which takes advantage of the rotational invariance by expanding the density
 variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\mathbf{r},\mathbf{\Omega})$
\end_inset

 on Wigner generalized spherical harmonics.
 In this algorithm, the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
acs{OZ}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 equation is largely simplified, and the memory needed for the storage of
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
acs{DCF}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is no longer important.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

The solvent properties involved in this thesis are presented in section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chpt:solvation-properties"

\end_inset

, organized in two aspects, the energy and the structure.
 The solvation free energy corrections and some forms of structure are presented.
